<subSubSection pageId="163" pageNumber="164" type="type">
<paragraph pageId="163" pageNumber="164">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="163" pageNumber="164">
CRIMEA, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="163" pageNumber="164">Yanata &amp; Doych</emphasis>
27/5/1913 (lectotype LE, designated here).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="163" pageNumber="164" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="163" pageNumber="164">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="163" pageNumber="164">
Perennial herb with leaves arranged in a basal rosette, from which arise erect stems 30-40 cm high; stems adpressed pilose. Leaves sessile, mostly basal, 2-5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.3-0. 5 cm, linear to oblanceolate, acute, tapered at the base to a pseudopetiole, adpressed pilose to subsericeous. Flowers congested at the top of the stem forming a headlike inflorescence with a single head arising from the uppermost leaf axil; bracts resembling linear-lanceolate reduced leaves, erect, slightly exceeding the inflorescence; peduncles of lateral capitula 2-22 mm, bracteoles filiform, pedicels 0-3 mm, sepals 14-15 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-6 mm, obovate, strongly cuspidate, adpressed pubescent and with a few spreading hairs, the inner sepals smaller; corolla 1.8-2 cm long, pink, midpetaline bands pilose; ovary hirsute; style pilose, divided 5 mm above the base; stigmas 4 mm. Capsule not seen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="163" pageNumber="164" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="163" pageNumber="164">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="163" pageNumber="164">
Crimea (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="163" pageNumber="164">Lindemann</emphasis>
s.n.).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="163" pageNumber="164" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="163" pageNumber="164">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="163" pageNumber="164">
This species appears to be almost certainly the hybrid between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="M. Bieb., Fl. Taur. - Caucas. 1: 147. 1808. (Marschall von Bieberstein" authorityYear="1808" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus holosericeus" order="Solanales" pageId="163" pageNumber="164" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="holosericeus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="163" pageNumber="164">Convolvulus holosericeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boiss., Diagn. Pl. Orient., ser. 2, 3: 124. 1856. (Boissier" authorityYear="1856" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus calvertii" order="Solanales" pageId="163" pageNumber="164" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="calvertii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="163" pageNumber="164">Convolvulus calvertii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, resembling the former in habit, leaf shape and indumentum but the latter in the presence of some spreading hairs on the sepals and the less saccate calyx. Unlike 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boiss., Diagn. Pl. Orient., ser. 2, 3: 124. 1856. (Boissier" authorityYear="1856" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus calvertii" order="Solanales" pageId="163" pageNumber="164" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="calvertii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="163" pageNumber="164">Convolvulus calvertii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the sparse indumentum makes the sepals clearly visible.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="163" pageNumber="164">
<bibRefCitation author="Juzepczuk, S" journalOrPublisher="Notulae Systematicae ex Herbario Instituti Botanici nomine VL Komarovii" pageId="204" pageNumber="205" pagination="212 - 222" refId="B169" refString="Juzepczuk, S, 1950. De &quot;Convolvulo Calverti&quot; Auctorum Florae Tauriae. Notulae Systematicae ex Herbario Instituti Botanici nomine VL Komarovii 12: 212 - 222" title="De &quot; Convolvulo Calverti &quot; Auctorum Florae Tauriae." volume="12" year="1950">Juzepczuk (1950)</bibRefCitation>
did not indicate type specimens for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Juz., Bot. Mater. Gerb. Bot. Inst. Komarova Akad. Nauk. S. S. S. R. 12: 219. 1950. (Juzepczuk" authorityYear="1950" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus sericocephalus" order="Solanales" pageId="163" pageNumber="164" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sericocephalus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="163" pageNumber="164">Convolvulus sericocephalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and a lectotype was incorrectly proposed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Smoljaninova, LA" journalOrPublisher="Flora of the European part of USSR" pageId="212" pageNumber="213" pagination="92 - 103" refId="B340" refString="Smoljaninova, LA, 1981. Convolvulaceae. Flora of the European part of USSR volume 5: 92 - 103" title="Convolvulaceae." volume="volume 5" year="1981">Smolyaninonova (1981)</bibRefCitation>
with the location as &quot;Zapadnaya storona Fyeodosiskovo shosse&quot; but without specimen citation. This appears to refer to 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="163" pageNumber="164">Yanata &amp; Doych</emphasis>
s.n. [27/5/1913], designated as lectotype above and, incidentally, the only specimen of this taxon seen by 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sa’ad">Sa'ad</normalizedToken>
. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sa’ad’s">Sa'ad's</normalizedToken>
citation of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="163" pageNumber="164">Juzepczuk</emphasis>
s.n. as the type is an inexplicable error as Juzepczuk does not cite any of his own collections.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
